Eiffel example converting an Eiffel string into a C string 

Compilation:
-----------
From scratch, on Unix:
Type
   	make -f Makefile.<platform>
and run 
	tst

From scratch, on Windows: (adjust your flags CC, CFLAGS if you are not using VC++)
In the Ace.ace file comment and uncomment the indicated lines (in external clause).
type
	set ISE_EIFFEL=<YOUR_INSTALLATION_DIRECTORY>
		where <YOUR_INSTALLATION_DIRECTORY> is the directory where you installed
		the Eiffel 4 delivery (ex: c:\Eiffel4)
	nmake -f Makefile.win
and run
	tst

Other:

	o to regenerate the object file fext.o:
		make -f Makefile.<platform> fext.o (on Unix)
		nmake -f Makefile.win fext.obj (on windows with VC++)
	o to recompile the eiffel system without changing the external
		ec -project tst.epr	(v4.3)
	o to recompile the eiffel system and link it with new external object file.
		ec -freeze -project tst.epr (v4.3)
	o to relink the eiffel system with new object file.
		cd EIFGEN/W_code; make; cd ../.. (use nmake with VC++)
	The new executable will be in EIFGEN\W_code directory on windows.
Release notes:
-------------

	With ISE Eiffel compilers anterior to 4.3, replace 
		tst.melted
	by 
		melted.eif 
	in the makefile file.

	On windows, you should the Ace option: "console_application(yes)" is
	only available on ISE Eiffel 4.3. This runs the exectable in the 
	the MS-DOS shell.
	prompt. On older compiler, you must edit the EIFGEN/W_code/tst.lnk file after compilation and replace
		-SUBSYSTEM:WINDOWS
	by
		-SUBSYSTEM:CONSOLE
	and then run
		link @tst.lnk
